Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: Today, the Arts District remains the home of many artists as well as those in other creative industries, including green technology, architecture, and entertainment, while still retaining some of its industrial use. Yet it is poised for another wave of development and change that comes with its own set of challenges. The area continues to attract new residential and commercial development, some of it now being built from the ground up and at a much larger scale than the existing structures.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: Located in the heart of L.A.’s burgeoning Arts District, Third & Traction is a mixed-use complex combining unique and thoughtfully-integrated retail, restaurant, live/work, and public gathering spaces. RYDA’s renovation transformed the property into a distinctive hub for the local community, amplifying its most successful features while evolving it for modern use. Originally built in 1910 by prominent design firm Richards-Neustadt Construction Company, this historic site has lived many lives, transforming from baking supply warehouse to envelope manufacturing plant to artist-in-residence space throughout the twentieth century. Aiming to preserve the building’s industrial character while augmenting its functionality, RYDA carefully restored its existing brickwork, integrating understated Beaux-Arts detailing on the façade.Just beyond the property’s ground-floor retail spaces, the Courtyard at Third & Traction is an intimate respite from the bustling streetscape. The sunny patio offers a publicly-accessible yet pleasantly secluded space for meeting a friend, enjoying a meal, or relaxing with a cocktail. The lushly greened rooftop restaurant space enjoys abundant sunlight from the neighborhood’s low skyline and sits in view of several expansive murals characteristic of the area

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: From its origin in 1914 as the home for the LL Burns Western Costume Company to its recent renovation and restoration as the HQ for Tarina Tarantino’s famed Sparkle Factory brand of jewelry, 908 S. Broadway has lived an illustrious life woven into the fabric of the Angeleno culture of Art and Entertainment. Designed by famed architects Meyer and Holler, known for their other LA icons – Grauman’s Chinese and Egyptian Theatres, 908 S. Broadway has been enriched through its history by instances such as its “starring role” in the famous “man hanging from clock scene” from the 1923 silent film “Safety Last”, to its most recent choice by notorious underground street artist Banksy as his canvas for the “Girl on Swing” art installment. The energy from its famed artists of both past and present that have found inspiration within its walls can be felt the moment you step through the doors. The stage is set and the new blank canvas is awaiting. Will you be the next chapter in this rich LA story?

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: 1370 N St. Andrews Place is in the developing area of Hollywood surrounded by the major content producers of our time. By being surrounded by some of the most creative and revolutionary companies in the world there is certainly no shortage of talent and inspiration. By being located in Hollywood you will be right in the action of fine dining mixed with entertainment and nightlife.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Originally designed by Paul R. Williams, famed architect to the stars, this historic 30,000-square-foot Colonial Revival building was reimagined into a midcentury marvel by Spanish Architectural firm SelgasCano. Decades apart these two visionaries have unwittingly become partners, fusing the timelessness of the past with a forward-thinking design that embodies the future workplace. A former Hollywood parking lot has been transformed into a two-acre site with a sprawling, creative office campus designed with a modern approach. Located in the heart of Hollywood, this thriving campus offers businesses an immeasurable opportunity to be seen as an anchor in the community.

SelgasCano reinvented the workplace cubicle, by creating “studios,” encased in faceted glass from desk height up, with sound-buffering carpet below. Long, wavy-edged team desks, punctuated by eclectic table lamps, line the interiors. An outdoor fountain and grand stairway lead into the main building and reflect the architect’s vision of a hip, fresh and imaginative design that aligns with the rest of the campus. Outside the main building, the site is encompassed by sixty oval-shaped office pods of varying sizes, which are topped with bright yellow rooftops, outfitted with glass walls and are each independent of the others. 

The campus already features all of the new air quality, hygienic components and social distancing measures that employees need to feel safe and secure when returning to the office.
The garden office pods are stand-alone buildings with individual air filtration systems that pump in fresh air directly from the outdoors and are coupled with operable windows that maximize the level of indoor air quality. Hospital-grade MERV-13 air filters in all common areas capture and flush out airborne toxins and contaminates – this simply can’t be replicated and is unique to this campus. Every detail has been architect-designed with health and safety in mind. Used throughout are Corian desks and countertops, a certified hygienic non-porous material that is widely used in hospitals and can easily be sanitized, touch-free light switches with motion sensors to keep microbes at bay, and single-story pods finished with polished concrete floors are a sampling of the measures taken to keep employees safe and secure during a time of uncertainty in the workplace.
